@@yThe Eastern Desert@@N

  Before empires raised pyramids, the eastern waste was governed by
surveyors called the @@eKeepers of Measure@@N. They ruled not by armies
but by calibration: road stones set to star angles, cistern basins
graded by seasonal drift, and caravan levies assessed in water rights
rather than coin. The desert was governable if measured correctly.

  They built the @@yTwelve Obelisk Lines@@N not as monuments but as
instruments. At dawn and dusk, their shadows marked legal travel
windows, ration allotment days, and safe convoy departure periods.
Each glyph on the obelisk faces encoded a compound meaning: direction,
time, water volume, and legal status in a single symbol. To inscribe
was to adjudicate.

  As traffic grew, merchant houses transformed survey law into hereditary
power. The @@ySalt Ledger Kingdoms@@N tracked water debt on crystalline
tablets. Nobility depended on logistics legitimacy -- a ruler was
accepted only if routes stayed open and cistern accounts balanced.

  The @@yCharter Road@@N system regulated all movement. Charter stones bore
distance, toll rate, and witness seals. Convoys obeyed minimum spacing
to prevent well depletion. Night travel was prohibited because the
obelisk shadow-measurement system was useless after dark.

  The @@dIseth Reach@@N -- a vanished river whose seasonal floods once
sustained the corridor -- dried and destabilized everything. Water
courts became war tribunals. The @@rCharter Wars@@N erupted as armed
survey crews enforced legal documents at spearpoint.

  The @@rJackal Synod@@N rose from militarized funerary priesthoods turned
toll enforcers. Three rival schools persist: the Anointers of
Continuance who preserve any remnant of regnal command, the Keepers
of Dry Mercy who ration suffering rather than maximize it, and the
@@rEclipsed Tongues@@N who seek total depopulation of the old roads.

  The @@dLast Sand Regent@@N -- preserved by a failed eclipse rite meant to
suspend drought -- still issues decrees to a dead bureaucracy in the
deepest necropolis. A policy engine with a royal memory, governing
in the language of duty while annihilating the living world it claims
to safeguard.

  Modern caravans cross the old road only under armed charter, passing
ruins of a civilization whose legal innovations echo in distant cities:
Kowloon's covenant bureaucracy, Kiess's trade syndic protocols, and
Midgaard's archival traditions all bear the fingerprints of
Keeper-of-Measure law.
